`set_child()` is a simple piece of syntactic sugar for the swapping out child nodes. It adds a node as a child, while also giving that node the supplied name. If child a with that name already exists, the old node is removed and freed. The main point is to allow nodes to work as simple state machines.

For a example if someone wanted a character to control differently depending on whether they are on land or water, they could do the following:

```
extend Node2D

func _ready():
   set_child( "controls", LandControls.new() )
 # …

class LandControls:
  # …
  func _fixed_process(delta):
    # land controls
    if is_in_water():
      get_parent().set_child( "controls", WaterControls.new() )

class WaterControls:
  # …
  func _fixed_process(delta):
    # water controls
    if not is_in_water():
      get_parent.set_child( "controls", LandControls.new() )
```
